'''Kamo Shrine''' (賀茂神社) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Tottori Prefecture|ja|鳥取県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Saiboku District|ja|西伯郡|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Nanbu Town|ja|南部町 (鳥取県)|lt=Nanbu Town|lt_ja=南部町|12=draft|12=draft}} Yamato. Its former {{ill|Shrine Rank|ja|社格|12=draft|12=draft}} was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|近代社格制度#諸社|lt=Gōsha|lt_ja=郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=474}}.

== History ==
The founding date is unknown. It is said that a {{ill|Branch Spirit|ja|分霊|lt=Branch Spirit|lt_ja=御分霊|12=draft|12=draft}} was transferred from Kyoto’s {{ill|Kamo Betsurai Shrine|ja|賀茂別雷神社|12=draft|12=draft}} and enshrined at the summit of Ōnaru-yama (大平山). Later it was moved to a place called Kobira on the mid-slope of the same mountain, and finally transferred to the foot of the mountain {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=474}}.

During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|lt=Sengoku period|lt_ja=戦国時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, when {{ill|Amago Tsunehisa|ja|尼子経久|12=draft|12=draft}} controlled {{ill|Hōki Province|ja|伯耆国|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was deeply revered; not only was an offering equivalent to 100 koku donated, but frequent visits, prayers, offerings, and shrine building were performed. However, with the downfall of the {{ill|Amago clan|ja|尼子氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine gradually declined {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=474}}. In the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, in {{ill|1733|ja|1733rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Kyōhō|ja|享保|12=draft|12=draft}} 18), the lord of the {{ill|Tottori Domain|ja|鳥取藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ikeda clan|ja|池田氏#鳥取藩主家|lt=Ikeda clan|lt_ja=池田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, donated an additional 10 koku. In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 5) in April it was classified as a Gōsha, and on {{ill|February 3|ja|2月3日|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|1907|ja|1907th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meiji 40) it was designated as a {{ill|Shinsenheihaku Rikyō Shrine|ja|近代社格制度#神饌幣帛料供進社|lt=Shinsenheihaku Rikyō Shrine|lt_ja=神饌幣帛料供進社|12=draft|12=draft}} {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=475}}. It served as the tutelary shrine for the seven villages of {{ill|Inokoji|ja|猪小路|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hokuhō|ja|北方|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hara|ja|原|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kobara|ja|小原|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinshō|ja|新庄|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kami-Aga|ja|上阿賀|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Shimo-Aga|ja|下阿賀|12=draft|12=draft}}, and was known as {{ill|Kamo Daimyōjin|ja|賀茂大明神|12=draft|12=draft}} until the early modern period {{Sfn|鳥取縣神社廰|2024}}.

In May {{ill|1916|ja|1916th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Taishō era|ja|大正|12=draft|12=draft}} 5), the unranked {{ill|Hokuhō Shrine|ja|北方神社|12=draft|12=draft}}—enshrined at Miyano-Tōge-yama in the Hokuhō district of {{ill|Ōkuni Village|ja|大国村 (鳥取県)|lt=Ōkuni Village|lt_ja=大国村|12=draft|12=draft}}—and the unranked {{ill|Kobara Shrine|ja|小原神社|12=draft|12=draft}}—enshrined at Kyakuno Mae in the same village—were merged with, on {{ill|April 30|ja|4月30日|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|1917|ja|1917th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Taishō era|ja|大正|12=draft|12=draft}} 6), the unranked {{ill|Aga Shrine|ja|阿賀神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (enshrined at Oga, Oji Kiriyama in the large district of Aga in {{ill|Tenshin Village|ja|天津村 (鳥取県)|lt=Tenshin Village|lt_ja=天津村|12=draft|12=draft}}) and the unranked {{ill|Tanabe Shrine|ja|田邊神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (enshrined at Towoben Kandō in the same village) through a {{ill|Shrine Merger|ja|神社合祀|lt=Shrine Merger|lt_ja=合併|12=draft|12=draft}} {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=475}}.

=== Shrine within the precincts ===
'''{{ill|Tadasu Shrine|ja|糺神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''' (ただすじんじゃ) is believed to have been founded at the same time as the main shrine, and together they were referred to as either '''{{ill|Kamo Ryōsha|ja|賀茂両社|12=draft|12=draft}}''' or '''{{ill|Kamo Shimokami Daimyōjin|ja|賀茂下上大明神|12=draft|12=draft}}''' {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=475}}.

'''{{ill|Sagi Shrine|ja|鷺神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''' (さぎじんじゃ) has an unknown founding date {{Sfn|石破|2000|p=31}}. It was originally enshrined at Watada Pass on the border of {{ill|Unpaku|ja|雲伯|12=draft|12=draft}}—a location commonly known as “Smallpox Pass”. It had long been venerated as the {{ill|Smallpox God|ja|疱瘡神|12=draft|12=draft}}, and served as a prayer site for the former lord {{ill|Ikeda clan|ja|池田氏|12=draft|12=draft}} {{Sfn|鳥取県神職会|1935|p=475}}. In October {{ill|1897|ja|1897th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 30) the shrine building was destroyed by fire, but it was rebuilt in May {{ill|1905|ja|1905th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meiji 38). In {{ill|1916|ja|1916th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Taishō 5) the {{ill|Tanaka Shrine|ja|田中神社|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Inokoji|ja|猪小路|12=draft|12=draft}} (enshrining deity: {{ill|Iwanagahime-no-mikoto|ja|イワナガヒメ|1=Iwanaga-hime|lt=Iwanagahime-no-mikoto|lt_ja=磐長姫命|12=draft|12=draft}}) was merged, and in {{ill|1917|ja|1917th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Taishō 6) it was transferred from Watada Pass to the current precincts of Kamo Shrine {{Sfn|石破|2000|p=31}}.

